<TEXT>
mario savio called himself not just an aging 
rabblerouser but a parent also as the pioneer of the student 
movement of the 1960s spoke at his sons graduation from a 
prestigious washington high school 
the onetime university of california at berkeley firebrand who 
helped trigger the student power movement also described his change 
during college from being a most unpolitical son of unpolitical 
italian immigrants 
we came to view america as a racist and imperialist power 
that covered its tracks with a beguiling opportunity for self 
expression the 45yearold told the class at sidwell friends 
school 
it was always right now in the 60s freedom now peace 
now he said did we not know that we could spoil the work by 
the way we dashed it off we lived our lives as if we might not 
live to the ripe old age of 30 even so we did not leave all 
our eggs in one basket we bore children 
savios son 18yearold nadav savio who plans to attend 
wesleyan university in connecticut not berkeley told the 
washington post for a story in saturdays editions that he has not 
become involved in political issues 
some of what happened in the 1960s was excessive he said 
there was random and rampant drug experimentation some 
people went overboard in various ways but there was a lot of good 
feeling among people and between people and thats something that 
should be resurrected 
savio who dropped out of berkeley in the mid1960s finally 
received his bachelors degree in 1984 from san francisco state 
university he is now a graduate student and parttime lecturer in 
physics at san francisco state 
nadav savio lives in washington with his mother suzanne 
goldberg a psychologist who is married to dr sidney wolfe 
director of the public citizen health research group a ralph nader 
organization 
savio is married for a second time and lives with his wife and 
their child in san francisco 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

