<TEXT>
a leader nicaraguan resistance leader says 
contra forces could face annihilation at the hands of the 
sandinistas unless the united states resumes military aid to the 
rebels 
the contra leader adolfo calero said friday at a news 
conference the aid was needed because of sandinista threats to wipe 
out the insurgents if the latest round of peace talks did not 
produce a final settlement to the nicaraguan war 
peace talks between the leftist sandinista government and the 
contras collapsed in managua thursday although both sides said a 
temporary truce would remain in effect 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said reagan was 
disappointed at the sandinista rejection of the nicaraguan 
resistance proposal to achieve democracy and an end to the war in 
nicaragua 
the reagan administration blamed the nicaraguan government for 
the breakdown in talks but said no decision had been made about 
whether to ask congress for more aid for the insurgents 
i think that in view of the sandinistas actions here their 
unwillingness to negotiate in good faith their unwillingness to 
instill democratic reforms you may well see a press for contra aid 
from members of the congress and from people in nicaragua and from 
other sources but at this point we have made no decisions said 
fitzwater 
meanwhile rep jack kemp rny urged the white house to 
propose an aid package for the contras that matches the amount of 
military assistance he said the soviet union provided to the 
sandinista government during the first three months of this year 
he put the amount at 105 million 
calero indicated he felt that was a reasonable amount the 
rebels have received no military aid since feb 29 the house 
rejected president reagans last military aid request for the 
contras on feb 3 
but rep david bonior dmich a leader of the anticontra 
forces in the house said this is no time to be talking of 
military aid he called for additional efforts to achieve a peace 
settlement before a new military aid request is considered 
the goal of the latest negotiating round which began on 
tuesday was to end the war and install democratic reforms in 
accordance with a preliminary peace plan signed on march 23 in 
sapoa nicaragua 
the discussions had been described as the fourth and final round 
of a series which have taken place under an interim truce 
</TEXT>
