<TEXT>
south koreas automotive industry 
gripped by prolonged labor disputes has lost more than 15 
billion in production and exports the trade and industry ministry 
reported today 
the ministry said lost production of parts and automobiles was 
estimated at 132 billion since january car export goals for the 
period were down by 37330 vehicles worth 219 million 
ministry officials said they feared korean auto exports may fall 
far short of a yearend goal of 756000 vehicles if the labor 
problems continued 
hyundai motor co the countrys largest automaker has been 
struck since may 30 with its assemly plant in ulsan on the east 
coast shut down completely strikers are demanding higher pay and 
better conditions 
hyundai officials said there was no immediate indication when 
suspended unionmanagement wage talks would resume they said both 
parties remained far apart on the extent of wage hikes 
the union demanded an increase of 48 percent or about 180 a 
month while the management offered a 25 percent raise or about 
100 
daewoo motor co the second biggest automaker was hit by 
strikes at its main plant near seoul in april the automaker is a 
joint venture between korean interests and general motors corp of 
the united states 
operations at the plants of kia motors corp partly owned by 
ford motor co and two other smaller companies were also reported 
suffering from prolonged wage disputes or a lack of key parts 
caused by strikes at parts suppliers 
production operations have been suspended or reduced at about 
500 parts makers for many weeks due to labor strikes sabotage or 
other problems with 600 other companies in normal operation 
some of the affected parts makers have asked for emergency 
bailout loans saying they face bankruptcy but monetary authorities 
were reportedly reluctant to comply with the requests citing the 
governments tight money policy to counter feared inflation 
last year south korea produced one million cars and commercial 
vehicles and exported 540000 of them 
</TEXT>
