<TEXT>
southern and central californians were jolted 
by a strong earthquake that sent rocks flying onto a freeway and 
closed an aqueduct that supplies half of los angeles water 
three people in nearby whittier were injured by a falling 
avocado tree in fridays earthquake one woman was treated at the 
scene and two men were taken to a hospital for tests 
the quake forced the closure of the 440milelong california 
aqueduct when power to at least two pumping plants was knocked out 
the temblor measuring 52 on the richter scale struck at 406 
pm and was centered on the garlock fault 11 miles 
northnortheast of gorman or about 70 miles northwest of downtown 
los angeles said robert finn a spokesman for the california 
institute of technology in pasadena 
state department of water resources officials in sacramento said 
crews worked overnight to reopen the aqueduct and that the city 
should not face a water shortage 
for la theres no problem the storage lakes have an ample 
water supply said mike mcgregor a spokesman for the state 
department of water resources he said the aqueduct would remain 
closed at least through today 
but he said the antelope valleyeast kern water district about 
50 miles north of downtown los angeles was asked to conserve 
because it had a smaller supply 
the quake catapulted rocks onto the northbound lanes of 
interstate 5 near the grapevine but traffic continued to flow 
while crews removed the rocks said california highway patrol 
officer jerry berger at the fort tejon station there were no 
immediate reports of accidents from the rockslide he said 
it was a real violent jolt berger said 
a series of aftershocks also were measured by caltech with the 
biggest measuring 40 on the richter scale at 422 pm said riley 
geary a seismic analyst 
the garlock fault where the quake struck is the secondlargest 
fault in california with a length of 200 miles compared with the 
600milelong san andreas fault said us geological survey 
seismologist lucile jones 
the richter scale measures ground motion as recorded on 
seismographs every increase of one number means a tenfold increase 
in magnitude thus a reading of 75 reflects an earthquake 10 times 
stronger than one of 65 
an earthquake of 35 on the richter scale can cause slight 
damage in the local area 4 moderate damage 5 considerable damage 
6 severe damage a 7 reading is a major earthquake capable of 
widespread heavy damage 8 is a great quake capable of 
tremendous damage 
the san francisco earthquake of 1906 which occurred before the 
richter scale was devised has been estimated at 83 on the richter 
scale 
