daimlerbenz the largest industrial 
conglomerate in west germany will pay 117 million to victims of 
nazi forced labor programs and their families red cross officials 
announced 
daimlerbenz makes cars buses and mercedesbenz luxury 
automobiles while its wideranging subsidiaries also include a 
major aerospace manufacturer 
like other german companies during adolf hitlers third reich 
daimler used forced laborers to fuel the nazi war effort 
with the payment daimlerbenz joins other major german 
companies who have paid reparations to former forced laborers and 
their families in 1986 the giant flick conglomerate paid 29 
million to slave labor victims 
other west german firms such as the giant krupp concern a 
major weapons producer during world war ii also have paid 
reparations 
the announcement of daimlers payments follows a lengthy study 
the company commissioned to determine the extent to which forced 
laborers worked in its plants nearly a half century ago 
thousands of workers died from illtreatment or were murdered in 
concentration camps if they were no longer able to work 
the german red cross in a telex statement to the news media on 
friday said it expected to receive 29 million from the automaker 
to distribute to forced labor victims in france belgium and the 
netherlands 
the red cross located in bonn said a total of 117 million 
would be paid by daimlerbenz to those affected and their family 
members 
it was not immediately known who would receive the rest of the 
money but the red cross said in the telex to news media that the 
donations were all intended for victims and their families living 
outside west germany 
daimlerbenz officials have scheduled a news conference for 
monday at which they were expected to announce further details of 
the payment plan they declined to give details of the payment 
program on friday 
</TEXT>
