<TEXT>
a federal agency seeking to make highlevel 
government service more attractive is recommending some officials 
be permitted to postpone taxes on profits resulting from property 
sold to avoid a conflict of interest with their public duties 
the administrative conference of the united states meeting 
thursday and friday proposed the deferral of tax liability in 
cases where the incoming official reinvests the proceeds of the 
sale in mutual funds congress would have to change the tax laws to 
permit this 
the conference a permanent independent agency established by 
congress to improve the working of federal agencies proposed that 
the tax postponement be available only in cases specifically 
requested by the president 
under current law officials who are forced to sell off property 
because they might present conflicts of interest must pay any 
capital gains taxes during the year of the sale 
you shouldnt have a tax penalty to become a public servant 
said fred j fielding a former reagan white house counsel who 
chairs the conferences special committee on ethics in government 
the conference also recommended that president reagan sign an 
executive order that later this year would require members of the 
incoming presidents transition team to agree in writing to a code 
of conduct 
during the 19801981 presidential transition over 600 persons 
most serving as volunteers had active assignments on agency 
transition teams the group said 
while it has no knowledge of any abuse the group said so many 
people dealing with federal agencies offers the potential for 
conflicts of interest or abuse of the public trust that accompanies 
their special access to government information and facilities 
the proposed conduct code for transition employees most of whom 
are not paid and do not join the government would prohibit them 
from using disclosing or permitting others to use for private gain 
any information they obtained in their temporary roles 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

