<TEXT>
a sheriffs deputy whose fingernails are a 
quarterinch over regulation was suspended for four days after she 
refused to trim them saying shes had them long all her 10 years 
on the job and they dont interfere with her work 
danielle rogers who works at the hennepin county juvenile 
center has nails that are threeeighths inch past her fingertips 
a grooming policy adopted by the sheriffs department may 16 says 
nails may not be longer than an eighth of an inch 
the policy covers a range of subjects including the length and 
style of hair personal hygiene and wearing jewelry 
rogers filed a grievance over the policy claiming it is an 
issue that should have been decided in collective bargaining 
between department officials and the deputies union she was 
suspended wednesday for a day for violating the rule and again on 
thursday this time for three days for not trimming her nails 
on friday the union filed suit against hennepin county and 
sheriff don omodt claiming that the failure to negotiate the 
policy was an unfair labor practice and that rogers was disciplined 
for exercising her right to file a grievance 
hennepin county district judge ann montgomery denied a temporary 
restraining order friday and scheduled a hearing for monday on 
whether a preliminary injunction should be issued 
omodt did not return a telephone call to the department 
saturday his home telephone is unlisted 
in an affidavit filed with the court rogers said she has had 
her nails the same length for the 10 years she has worked as a 
deputy and they do not affect her work 
the objection is not over the grooming policy said her 
attorney marshall tanick but over the failure of the county to 
bargain with the union he also said there is a right to privacy in 
personal appearance as long as it is not detrimental to the job 
another problem with the policy tanick said is that it does 
not spell out what the consequences are for violating it 
rogers has been threatened with disciplinary action up to 
dismissal according to court documents 
karla hancock assistant hennepin county attorney said friday 
there was no need to bargain about the policy because it falls 
under managements rights rather than being a term and condition 
of employment that must be negotiated 
said tanick we believe there are serious law enforcement 
issues in the county that merit attention too much time and energy 
has been devoted to this petty issue 
as long as the deputy is competentthe length of her nails 
should not matter 
