<TEXT>
in china a nation that takes its political 
slogans seriously a large billboard in a provincial capital 
reading efficiency is life time is money is a dramatic sign 
of the times 
it is an indication of how communist party ideologists the 
shapers of public opinion have been backed into a corner by the 
rapid acceptance of private ownership shareholding and free 
markets all capitalistic challenges to marxistleninist doctrine 
capitalism has absorbed things from socialism now we should 
absorb some good things from capitalism said zhao yao dean of 
the communist party central committee college a training ground 
for ideologists 
capitalism was once dismissed in china as an evil opposed to 
socialism 
but we now believe that was wrong added zhao 
the official doctrines that have often forced the chinese to 
worry about whether they are being good communists have been in a 
state of flux since deng xiaoping the pragmatist famed for saying 
it doesnt matter if a cat is black or white as long as it 
catches mice came to power 10 years ago 
declaring that poverty is not socialism he dismantled mao 
tsetungs communes restored the profit motive and unleashed 
freemarket forces into a rigid system of central planning 
today the concern of most chinese is how to get better wages 
and cope with rising prices 
as long as the economy is prosperous and living standards are 
raised our purpose is fulfilled said li yining a prominent 
economist 
this month the communist party will publish its last issue of 
the journal red flag whose heavy prose has for 30 years set 
the tone for party ideology in its place the party will 
inaugurate a publication called seeking truth which is 
expected to concentrate on economic reforms and political 
democratization 
party leader zhao ziyang a major supporter of economic reforms 
announced at a party conference last fall that china will be in 
what he called the primary stage of socialism through the 
middle of the next century 
zhao told economic planners they would be allowed to adapt 
capitalist practices as long as these advanced the national goal of 
economic development party propagandists hailed zhaos 
laissezfaire approach to socialism which played down the need for 
ideology to back up policy 
the guangming daily chinas leading intellectual newspaper 
said in a recent commentary that great changes have taken place in 
the past decade 
however we cannot deny that in many places dogmatism like a 
specter still binds the peoples thinking and hampers the 
development of socialist modernization it said adding that even 
these days almost every new economic or political reform must 
still overcome suspicions of being too capitalistic 
by adopting unorthodox approaches to marxism and capitalism the 
new theorists are trying to legitimize reforms that have brought 
china television commercials promoting consumption free markets 
taking away business from state stores and millionaires with 
servants 
many of the new theorists say the ideology of karl marx who 
lived in the 19th century cannot explain the modern relationship 
between socialism and capitalism they say maos insistence on 
class struggle over economic development was a disaster for china 
leading social scientist li honglin recently wrote that the 
soviet union once chinas model as an economic system has 
failed to match the productive energy of capitalist countries 
socialism is not a cake that can be ordered and there is no 
fixed pattern for socialism li wrote 
to promote reforms we must make breakthroughs in theory 
said zhao yao dean of the party central committee college 
shareholding private ownership of property and even the 
democratic process are other western practices that can be of use 
to chinese socialism the party school theorists said 
zhao said chinas 18 million private entrepreneurs have become 
an important auxiliary part of the economy 
but the party theorists insist that china remain a socialist 
country whose vital task is to define socialism to meet the 
countrys changing needs 
reflecting this task the chinese academy of social science has 
said it will this year start a new research project the study of 
a modified form of socialism 
the head of the research team will be one of chinas most 
progressive political thinkers su shaozhi who a year ago was 
fired from his position as head of the academys marxismleninism 
institute for being too liberal 
