ozals threeday visit to athens the first by a turkish 
premier in 36 years is the latest move to improve relations after 
a greekturkish summit at the swiss ski resort of davos in january 
we went to davos and agreed on a nowar course we havent 
ensured peace but were striving for consolidation of peace in the 
region papandreou recently told parliament 
fifteen months ago greece and turkey nearly went to war over 
oildrilling rights in the aegean in a flareup that apparently 
persuaded papandreou to change his hardline policy toward turkey 
for years the former american economics professor had rejected 
ozals offers of friendship suggesting that turkey had deeplaid 
plans to invade several greek islands near turkeys aegean coast 
papandreous antiturkish rhetoric struck a chord with greeks 
who view turkey with suspicion tinged with fear a legacy of four 
centuries of ottoman turkish rule in greece and periodic eruptions 
of violence over the past 30 years 
there were antigreek riots in turkey in the 1950s trouble 
over cyprus in the 60s and the turkish invasion of cyprus in 1974 
its hard to believe the turks really want to be friends said 
businessman ioakim papazoglou whose family used to live in turkey 
although greeks welcome the reduced tension the speed and style 
of papandreous policy switch has produced criticism from both 
conservatives and leftists 
perhaps the suddenness of davos took people by surprise but 
whats being done is a stepbystep process that will take a long 
