allegations that the manager of a northwestern 
ohio nuclear power plant was disruptive in the control room 
after drinking at a new years eve 1986 party have come under 
investigation on capitol hill officials say 
officials of toledo edison co the utility that operates the 
davisbesse nuclear power plant near toledo said however that 
their own investigation showed the manager was capable of carrying 
out his responsibilities despite his drinking 
john scheibel staff director for the house interior 
investigations subcommittee said friday the panels review of the 
incident at davisbesse is in its early stages 
were just taking a look at it preliminarily scheibel said 
a congressional source who spoke only on condition of anonymity 
said the house energy and commerce investigations subcommittee also 
has been reviewing the alleged incident for a couple of weeks 
in addition the nuclear regulatory commission is wrapping up 
its investigation into the allegations according to nrc spokesman 
jan strasma 
strasma said the nrc initially had accepted the findings of the 
investigation by toledo edison but started a new review last july 
after the agencys resident inspector received more information 
from plant employees 
toledo edison found that the plant manager had been drinking 
before arriving at the control room but concluded it is clear 
that the individual was in fact fully fit for duty accordingly no 
disciplinary action is recommended 
davisbesse about 20 miles east of toledo was shut down for 18 
months after a june 9 1985 incident in which two main and two 
backup feedwater pumps failed operators restarted the pumps and 
kept the reactor safely covered with cooling water since then the 
utility has spent about 180 million to upgrade the plant 
strasma said the plant was in the process of starting back up 
the evening of dec 31 1986 when the manager was called to the 
site to check progress 
the allegation was that this manager had been drinking and he 
was disruptive in the control room strasma said 
he said toledo edison submitted a report on the incident to the 
nrc on feb 19 1987 the report stated that the manager had been 
at a new years eve party at which he had consumed alcohol and that 
when he later went to the control room he was outspoken and 
argumentative strasma said 
the report quoted a person in the control room as characterizing 
the manager as angry and briefly outspoken but that the person 
did not think it surprising or inappropriate 
while the utilitys report substantiated that the manager was at 
the plant shortly after drinking alcohol it said the allegation 
that his behavior was distracting was subjective and not 
substantiated 
toledo edison spokesman richard kelly said the utility 
thoroughly investigated the matter and could find nothing to back 
up the allegation that the manager had been unfit for duty 
strasma said the manager currently retains his position with the 
utility 
the probe was taken over last october by the nrcs office of 
investigations which reviews possible wrongdoing by licensees 
said strasma who added that a report on the incident was being 
written 
