<TEXT>
the federal government must extend its 
amnesty deadline for illegal aliens who briefly left the country a 
federal judge ruled friday but refused to allow ousted aliens to 
return to the united states 
both the attorney general and the group representing the aliens 
catholic social services inc said they will appeal the ruling by 
us district court lawrence karlton 
karlton in an eightpage order ruled that aliens living in the 
us who left the country briefly without permission from the 
immigration and naturalization service should be allowed to apply 
for amnesty through the end of nov 30 a sixmonth extension of 
the deadline 
karlton also ruled that illegal aliens who lived in the us 
then left the country and were caught and deported when they tried 
to return should not be allowed to come back 
the order covering 50000 to 100000 people nationwide affects 
those who left the country after nov 6 1986 when the alien 
amnesty law took effect 
karltons decision was prompted by a lawsuit filed by catholic 
social services the california rural legal assistance and other 
immigrantrights groups 
the suit took issue with the definition of the words in the 
immigration law brief causal and innocent departures 
the phrase by congress was interpreted by the ins to mean trips 
of less than 30 days for a legitimate purpose with ins permission 
and that those who left the country without permission would not be 
eligible for amnesty 
the lawsuit contends that many aliens who hurriedly left the 
country for noncriminal reasons such as dealing with family 
emergencies were improperly denied amnesty eligibility when they 
returned 
the appeal of the ruling is expected to be filed next week in 
the 9th circuit court of appeals in san francisco 
 
