<TEXT>
hungary needs radical reforms and faces 
years of social upheaval before its economic and social crisis will 
end a private hungarian think tank said 
in a separate discussion on state television a top communist 
party official revealed that hungarys economic woes meant that its 
defense commitments to the warsaw pact were not increased this 
year and will not grow in real terms through 1990 
in a report friday the state news agency mti summarized what 
it said were the results of a report by the financial research co 
a former state institute that went private last year after 
communist authorities threatened to close it for its critical 
analyses 
the new analysis entitled reports from the tunnel said 
hungary now faces a criticial situation externally and 
internally because reforms begun in the late 1960s did not go far 
enough in dismantling centralized state control over the economy 
production is growing ever more slowly the situation of small 
business has become less stable the inflationary pressure remains 
the selfrestraint by companies about price increases will not 
last long and the efforts to curb budgetary spending have not been 
successful said istvan csillag deputy head of the research 
company 
inflation has already touched 18 percent in hungary this year 
and many experts expect it to go higher 
mti quoted csillag as saying that the currently favorable 
assessment of hungarys prospects abroad will soon change unless 
more reform is adopted 
with a gross hard currency debt of 18 billion hungary is 
highly dependent on western assessments of its performance and 
reforms to gain further credits from governments banks and the 
international monetary fund 
mti quoted the financial research co as saying significant 
changes were needed including a shift to satisfying overall market 
demand rather than selected markets and new forms of ownership 
if such changes were implemented the report said then we may 
be out of the present critical situation in five to eight years 
time 
but it noted that this would only occur at a price of the 
upheavals that structural change will entail 
mti quoted the firms manager marton tardos as saying it was 
necessary to create popular support for changes even if they 
entailed unemployment and other unpopular reductions in the social 
support mechanism 
until the mid1980s unemployment was unknown in hungary which 
like other soviet bloc nations touted full employment as one of the 
achievements of communism 
hungary and other east european nations have now admitted that 
people employed in unprofitable state enterprises will have to face 
at least temporary job loss as state subsidies are shifted from the 
lossmaking firms to more profitable enterprises 
one area of communist budgets that so far has seemed immune from 
cuts has been defense 
but politburo member miklos nemeth indicated on hungarian 
television thursday night that hungarys economic woes have also 
affected military spending 
he said 1987 defense spending including costs for ministry of 
interior militia and for clothing and housing soldiers totaled 
about 1 billion 
the real value of defense spending was not increased in 1988 
nemeth said declining to give figures 
warsaw pact commitments also were not increased as in the past 
but kept the same in real terms nemeth said again he provided no 
figures 
